Description of the data used for the exercise

In this exercise we use data colleced by Kimmo Vehkalahti between December 2014 and January 2015. Data consists of 166 students. The average (sd) age of the students was 25.5 years. Students filled out questionnaires about their learning strategies and attitudes towards statistics. The items measuring different dimensions (deep/surface/strategic) of learning strategies were averaged to summary scores (deep, stra, and surf). Attitude towards statistics was measured with 10 items, and answers to these items were averaged to summary score (attitude). All summary scores were measured in a scale from 1 to 5. The outcome variable was points obtained from a statistics exam (min 7, max 33).

Figure 2.1 A graphical overwiew of the data
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.4.4
## Warning: package 'GGally' was built under R version 3.4.4

A graphical overview of the data and summaries of the variables in the data are presented in the Figure 2.1. Out of students, approximately one third were men. Men were slightly older and had slightly better attitude towards statistics, even though based on boxplots, it is not possible to say if the differences were statistically significant. There were no clear differences in different dimensions of learning and exam points between genders.

Out of continuous variables, all except age were quite normally distributed. Age was skewed towards right, since most of the students were younger than 25 years old, but the oldest were around 50 years old. The highest correlation (0.437) was observed between attitude and exam points. Also strategic learning was positively correlated with exam points (0.146), whereas surface learning was negatively correlated with exam points (-0.144). Observed correlatios were similar in both genders. There seemed to be no association between age or deep learning and exam points.

Regression model

I chose to explain exam points with attitude and two dimensions of learning (stategic and surcafe), since those variables had the highest absolute correaltions with exam points. The summary of the regression model is presented in Table 2.1.

Table 2.1 Summary of the regression model with three explanatory variables (attitude, strategic learning and surface leargning). Dependent variable is exam points.

## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

Statistical test related to model parameters tests the null hypothesis that the beta estimate is 0. Summary of the fitted model shows that out of the examined variables, only attitude was significantly associated with exam points (p<0.001). The beta estimate was 3.4 meaning that if attitude towards statistics (on a scale from 1 to 5) increases one point, the exam points increase by 3.4 on average. As already mentioned, strategic and surface learning were not significantly associated with exam points. Their beta estimates were quite close to 0 (0.9 and -0.6 respectively) and p-values were over 0.5. The multiple R-squared was 0.21 meaning that these three variables together explained 21% of the variance in exam points.

In the second model, variables that did not have a statitically significant relationship with exam points (startegic and surface learning) were removed. The beta estimate of attitude increased to 3.5 (Table 2.2) and the result was still higly significant (p<0.001). Multiple R-squared was 0.19, meaning that attitude alone explained 19% of variance in exam points.

Model validation

In addition to assuming a linear association between explanatory and dependent variable, there are several assumptions regarding residuals (errors) in the linear regression:

  1. Residuals should be normally distributed
  2. Residuals should be indepent on the explanatory variable(s)
  3. Residuals should not be correlated

Model assumptions can be examined graphically with different plots (Figure 2.2). Residuals vs Fitted uncovers if the residuals are dependent on the explanatory variable. In this exercise, the assumption held and they residuals were not dependent on explanatory variable since the dots in the plot were quite randomly spread aroud the horizontal line and there was no clear pattern to be seen. Q-Q plot shows the normality of the residuals. In this exercise, the residuals were quite normally distributed, since the dots in the Q-Q plot fell nicely within the line. The last plot Residuals vs Leverage reveals if there are single cases which have unusually high impact on the model. In this exercise, there were no such cases because there were no single dots which stood out from the plot. The highest leverage (on the x axis) was around 0.05, which is quite small. In conclusion, the model met the assumptions very well.

Figure 2.2 Diagnostic plots for the second regression model (points ~ attitude)

Rstudio Exercise 3

Description of the data used for the exercise

In this exercise we use Student Performance Data Set which can be downloaded from Machine learning repository. The data includes students from two diffent Portugese schools (Gabriel Pereira and Mousinho da Silveira). The two original datasets with information about the performance in mathematics and portugese language were combined in dara wrangling part of this exercise. My Rscript for creating the analysis data can be found here in my GitHub repository. The combined data includes only subjects who had information about both mathematics and portugese language. Below the variable names of the data are printed. In this exercise we are especially interested in low vs. high alcohol consumption and different backround characteristics associated with it. Alcohol consumption is measured in a scale from 1/“very low” to 5/“very high” separately for workdays and weekend. High alcohol consumption refers to average alcohol consumption score higher than 2.

Choosing variables for analysis and setting hypothesis.

In this exercise, I’m going to study four interesting variables which might explain high alcohol consumption. I choose student’s gender (sex), mother’s education (Medu), extra-curricular activities (activites) and going out with friends (goout) as the variables of interest. I hypothesise:

  1. The risk of being “high user” is greater in boys compared to girls
  2. Mother’s higher education is related to less alcohol consumption
  3. Having extra curricular activities is associated with less alcohol consumption.
  4. Going out with friens is associated with higher alcohol consumption
Descriptive results of the variables of interest

## # A tibble: 4 x 3
## # Groups:   high_use [?]
##   high_use sex   count
##   <lgl>    <fct> <int>
## 1 FALSE    F       156
## 2 FALSE    M       112
## 3 TRUE     F        42
## 4 TRUE     M        72

As hypothesised, it looks like the sex is associated with alcohol use. There are more girls in low achohol use category whereas in high alcohol consumption category there are more boys.

The boxplots look so similar in both groups that mother’s education probably is not related to alcohol consumption. The observation is contradictory to my hypothesis, I assumed tha students with high alcohol consumption would have less educated mothers. Mother’s education probably should not be threated as continuous variable, but I did not have time find better solution for this variable.

## # A tibble: 4 x 3

Based on the crosstabulation above, it seems that there is no clear difference in alcohol consumption if student has or does not have extra-curricular activities. This is also contradictory to my hypothesis. I assumed that students with high alcohol consumption would have less extra-curricular activites. There might be a slight tendency towards that direction, but the diffences between high vs. low alchol consumption groups are not very large.

Based on the boxplot above it looks like going out is associated with high alcohol use. Students with high alcohol consumption had higher scores for goint out with friends. The observation is in line with my hypothesis.

As assumed when exploring the variables, only sex and going out are significantly associated with the alcohol consumtion, since the confidence intervals of ORs for these variables do not include 1. OR for boys is 2.6, meaning that boys have 2.6 times higher odds of high alcohol consumption compared to girls. OR for going out is 2.1, meaning that each 1 point increase in going out scale (from 1 to 5) is associated with 2.1 higher odds of high alcohol consumption.

Below the relationships of the variables are shown in a correlation matrix. Strong negative correaltions are found between dis (weighted distances to five Boston employment centres) and age (proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940), nox (nitric oxided concentration, and indus (proportion of non-retail business acres per town). This means that if the distance from the employment centres increases, the housing units are younger, there is less nitric oxid and less non-retail business acres. A quite strong negative correlation was also found between medv (median value of owner-occupied houses) and lstat (% lower status of the population), meaning that value of the houses increases there is less lower status population. Highest positive correaltion was found between rad and tax. Meaning that when accessibility to radial highways inreases, also the property tax-rate increases.

Creating the categorical crime variable and dividing the dataset

Frequencies of the new categorical crime-variable:

# creating a quantile vector of crim 
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

# removing original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# adding the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

table(boston_scaled$crime)
## 
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127

Next, the original data is divided into two datasets: “train” and “test”. The “train” dataset includes 80 % of the original observations and we used it to create a model to predict crime class. Then we test the model to predict the crime class in the “test” dataset.

#Dividing the dataset to two: test & train
# number of rows in the Boston dataset 
n <- nrow(Boston)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Predicting the classes with the LDA model on the test data.

Cross-tabulation of the correct vs. predicted crime classes in the test data:

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       10      11        1    0
##   med_low    7      14        4    0
##   med_high   2       7       19    1
##   high       0       0        0   26

From the cross-tabluation we can see that the model is quite good at predicting the high class, only one observation in med_high class is incorrectly predicted to be in high class. However, also in the other classes more than half of the observations are correctly classified using the prediction.
